During the Ash-and-Iron Decades, Midgaard magistrates issued sealed warrants condemning debtors and unregistered persons to labor service.
The Violet Compact's registry processed these people as "arcane material," stripping civic identity before transfer to the Spirebound Conclave.
The Conclave received transferred subjects for experimentation: the Ember Canon program (fire and will tests), the Prism Thesis program (crystal implantation), and the Pale Ledger program (spirit extraction and imprinting).
Sealed warrants were issued under emergency charter law and carried no appeal mechanism: once sealed, the warrant removed the named individual from the civic registry, eliminating their legal standing to contest the proceeding.
The mechanism was institutional, not individual: no single magistrate devised it. The Violet Compact's registry apparatus had been designed to process arcane material efficiently; extending that efficiency to human subjects required only a reclassification of what counted as "arcane material."
Three categories of people were most vulnerable: debtors with outstanding obligations to Midgaard's registry, "unregistered persons" (those who had arrived without ledger documentation), and populations designated as "human subtypes" including Ashborn.
Kiess's founding charter explicitly prohibits sealed warrants in direct response to this history; the anti-sealed-warrant clause was written knowing that Evermeet had participated in the same transfer apparatus.
The Spirebound Conclave's eventual collapse (seismic event plus internal sabotage) destroyed most evidence on the receiving end; the sealed warrants and Midgaard's trade ledgers are the best surviving administrative documentation.
The Continuity faction keeps the warrants sealed on grounds that opening them would create tribunal liability for institutional successors and destabilize the governance system that currently functions.
The Reckoning faction demands opening on grounds that the warrants contain the names of people who were processed as objects, and that their names are the historical record of an institutional atrocity.
Kowloon's Black Ledger contains parallel documentation from the delta settlements' participation in the same apparatus.

