Kowloon's sealed records from the Ash-and-Iron period parallel Midgaard's sealed warrants from the delta settlements' end of the same apparatus.
The Black Ledger's population lists correspond to the same transfer chain: Midgaard's warrants name subjects being transferred out; Kowloon's Black Ledger names subjects whose registry entries were stripped before transfer.
The institutional guilt is mutual: opening either city's records creates pressure to open the other's, and no city's Continuity faction wants to be first.
Kowloon's Neon Covenant was partly designed to prevent sealed warrants from being possible: the jade seal's two-magistrate requirement applies specifically to any proclamation removing a person from the civic registry.
