Mafdet's maritime legal tradition has no internal mechanism equivalent to sealed warrants — maritime law's oath attestation system cannot be sealed against the named party's knowledge without invalidating the oath.
An oath witnessed by a party who does not know they are being attested is void under maritime law; the sealed warrant's fundamental structure is therefore legally impossible under Mafdet's legal tradition.
The Strandline Compact's founding document includes a clause rejecting any warrant that "removes a party from the register of their own knowledge."
Mafdet's formal distance from the sealed warrant tradition is the basis for the Swift Court's role as a neutral forum in cargo disputes where one party is from a sealed-warrant governance tradition.
